# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: descriptive-complexity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Specifically, each logical system produces a set of queries expressible in it.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] The queries – when restricted to finite structures – correspond to the computational problems of traditional complexity theory.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] The first main result of descriptive complexity was Fagin's theorem, shown by Ronald Fagin in 1974.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] It established that NP is precisely the set of languages expressible by sentences of existential second-order logic; that is, second-order logic excluding universal quantification over relations, functions, and subsets.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Many other classes were later characterized in such a manner.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] When we use the logic formalism to describe a computational problem, the input is a finite structure, and the elements of that structure are the domain of discourse.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Usually the input is either a string (of bits or over an alphabet) and the elements of the logical structure represent positions of the string, or the input is a graph and the elements of the logical structure represent its vertices.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] The length of the input will be measured by the size of the respective structure.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] We also have constants, which are special elements of the respective structure, for example if we want to check reachability in a graph, we will have to choose two constants *s* (start) and *t* (terminal).
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] In descriptive complexity theory we often assume that there is a total order over the elements and that we can check equality between elements.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] This lets us consider elements as numbers: the element x represents the number n if and only if there are $(n-1)$ elements y with $y<x$ .
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Thanks to this we also may have the primitive predicate "bit", where $bit(x,k)$ is true if only the kth bit of the binary expansion of x is 1.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] (We can replace addition and multiplication by ternary relations such that $plus(x,y,z)$ is true if and only if $x+y=z$ and $times(x,y,z)$ is true if and only if $x*y=z$ ).
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] In circuit complexity, first-order logic with arbitrary predicates can be shown to be equal to AC0, the first class in the AC hierarchy.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Indeed, there is a natural translation from FO's symbols to nodes of circuits, with $\forall ,\exists$ being $\land$ and $\lor$ of size n.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] First-order logic in a signature with arithmetical predicates characterises the restriction of the AC0 family of circuits to those constructible in alternating logarithmic time.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] First-order logic in a signature with only the order relation corresponds to the set of star-free languages.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] First-order logic gains substantially in expressive power when it is augmented with an operator that computes the transitive closure of a binary relation.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] The resulting transitive closure logic is known to characterise non-deterministic logarithmic space (NL) on ordered structures.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] This was used by Immerman to show that NL is closed under complement (i. e. that NL = co-NL).
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] When restricting the transitive closure operator to deterministic transitive closure, the resulting logic exactly characterises logarithmic space on ordered structures.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] On structures that have a successor function, NL can also be characterised by second-order Krom formulae.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Every second-order Krom formula is equivalent to an existential second-order Krom formula.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] SO-Krom characterises NL on structures with a successor function.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] FO[LFP] is the extension of first-order logic by a least fixed-point operator, which expresses the fixed-point of a monotone expression.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] This augments first-order logic with the ability to express recursion.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] The Immerman–Vardi theorem, shown independently by Immerman and Vardi, shows that FO[LFP] characterises PTIME on ordered structures.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] As of 2025, it is still open whether there is a natural logic characterising PTIME on unordered structures.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] The Abiteboul–Vianu theorem states that FO[LFP]=FO[PFP] on all structures if and only if FO[LFP]=FO[PFP]; hence if and only if P=PSPACE.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] This result has been extended to other fixpoints.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] In the presence of a successor function, PTIME can also be characterised by second-order Horn formulae.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] This class is equal to P on structures with a successor function.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Those formulae can be transformed to prenex formulas in existential second-order Horn logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Ronald Fagin's 1974 proof that the complexity class NP was characterised exactly by those classes of structures axiomatizable in existential second-order logic was the starting point of descriptive complexity theory.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Since the complement of an existential formula is a universal formula, it follows immediately that co-NP is characterized by universal second-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] SO, unrestricted second-order logic, is equal to the Polynomial hierarchy PH.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] More precisely, we have the following generalisation of Fagin's theorem: The set of formulae in prenex normal form where existential and universal quantifiers of second order alternate *k* times characterise the *k*th level of the polynomial hierarchy.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Unlike most other characterisations of complexity classes, Fagin's theorem and its generalisation do not presuppose a total ordering on the structures.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] This is because existential second-order logic is itself sufficiently expressive to refer to the possible total orders on a structure using second-order variables.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] The class of all problems computable in polynomial space, PSPACE, can be characterised by augmenting first-order logic with a more expressive partial fixed-point operator.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Partial fixed-point logic, FO[PFP], is the extension of first-order logic with a partial fixed-point operator, which expresses the fixed-point of a formula if there is one and returns 'false' otherwise.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Partial fixed-point logic characterises PSPACE on ordered structures.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Second-order logic can be extended by a transitive closure operator in the same way as first-order logic, resulting in SO[TC].
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] The TC operator can now also take second-order variables as argument.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Since ordering can be referenced in second-order logic, this characterisation does not presuppose ordered structures.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] The time complexity class ELEMENTARY of elementary functions can be characterised by **HO**, the complexity class of structures that can be recognized by formulas of higher-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Higher-order logic is an extension of first-order logic and second-order logic with higher-order quantifiers.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] There is a relation between the i th order and non-deterministic algorithms the time of which is bounded by $i-1$ levels of exponentials.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] A variable of order $i>1$ has an arity k and represents any set of k -tuples of elements of order $i-1$ .
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] They are usually written in upper-case and with a natural number as exponent to indicate the order.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Higher-order logic is the set of first-order formulae where we add quantification over higher-order variables; hence we will use the terms defined in the FO article without defining them again.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] HO $^{i}$ is the set of formulae with variables of order at most i .
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] So HO $_{j}^{i}$ is the set of formulae with j alternations of quantifiers of order i , beginning with $\exists$ , followed by a formula of order $i-1$ .
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] Every formula of order i th is equivalent to a formula in prenex normal form, where we first write quantification over variable of i th order and then a formula of order $i-1$ in normal form.
[src:descriptive-complexity/descriptive-complexity-theory] HO is equal to the class ELEMENTARY of elementary functions.
[src:descriptive-complexity/fagin-s-theorem] It was proven by Ronald Fagin in 1973 in his doctoral thesis, and appears in his 1974 paper.
[src:descriptive-complexity/fagin-s-theorem] The arity required by the second-order formula was improved (in one direction) by James Lynch in 1981, and several results of Étienne Grandjean have provided tighter bounds on nondeterministic random-access machines.
[src:descriptive-complexity/fagin-s-theorem] For example, consider the problem of deciding if a graph is 3-colorable.
[src:descriptive-complexity/fagin-s-theorem] By Fagin’s theorem, there is a second order existential formula $\phi$ , such that a graph is 3-colorable if and only if the graph, as a finite model for $\phi$ , semantically implies $\phi$ .
[src:descriptive-complexity/fagin-s-theorem] In this formula, A, B, or C are to be interpreted as the sets of vertices colored with the 3 colors, and E(v, w) is to be interpreted as saying the vertices v, w share an edge.
[src:descriptive-complexity/fagin-s-theorem] The formula then states that no two adjacent vertices have the same color.
[src:descriptive-complexity/fagin-s-theorem] Note that there is no need to explicitly enforce each vertex to have *exactly* 1 color, just at least 1 color.
[src:descriptive-complexity/fagin-s-theorem] Since, if we allow more than 1 color per vertex, and no two adjacent vertices have the same color, then we certainly can have each vertex to have exactly 1 color, and still no two adjacent vertices have the same color.
[src:descriptive-complexity/fagin-s-theorem] The 1999 textbook by Immerman provides a detailed proof of the theorem.
[src:descriptive-complexity/fagin-s-theorem] To do so, one can use second-order existential quantifiers to arbitrarily choose a computation tableau.
[src:descriptive-complexity/fagin-s-theorem] In more detail, for every timestep of an execution trace of a non-deterministic Turing machine, this tableau encodes the state of the Turing machine, its position in the tape, the contents of every tape cell, and which nondeterministic choice the machine makes at that step.
[src:descriptive-complexity/fagin-s-theorem] A first-order formula can constrain this encoded information so that it describes a valid execution trace, one in which the tape contents and Turing machine state and position at each timestep follow from the previous timestep.
[src:descriptive-complexity/fagin-s-theorem] A key lemma used in the proof is that it is possible to encode a linear order of length $n^{k}$ (such as the linear orders of timesteps and tape contents at any timestep) as a $2k$ -ary relation R on a universe A of size n .
[src:descriptive-complexity/fagin-s-theorem] One way to achieve this is to choose a linear ordering L of A and then define R to be the lexicographical ordering of k -tuples from A with respect to L .
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Since many central theorems of model theory do not hold when restricted to finite structures, finite model theory is quite different from model theory in its methods of proof.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Central results of classical model theory that fail for finite structures under finite model theory include the compactness theorem, Gödel's completeness theorem, and the method of ultraproducts for first-order logic (FO).
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] These invalidities all follow from Trakhtenbrot's theorem.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] While model theory has many applications to mathematical algebra, finite model theory became an "unusually effective" instrument in computer science.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] In other words: "In the history of mathematical logic most interest has concentrated on infinite structures. [...] Yet, the objects computers have and hold are always finite.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] To study computation we need a theory of finite structures." Thus the main application areas of finite model theory are: descriptive complexity theory, database theory and formal language theory.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] A common motivating question in finite model theory is whether a given class of structures can be described in a given language.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] For instance, one might ask whether the class of cyclic graphs can be distinguished among graphs by a FO sentence, which can also be phrased as asking whether cyclicity is FO-expressible.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] A single finite structure can always be axiomatized in first-order logic, where axiomatized in a language *L* means described uniquely up to isomorphism by a single *L*-sentence.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Similarly, any finite collection of finite structures can always be axiomatized in first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Some, but not all, infinite collections of finite structures can also be axiomatized by a single first-order sentence.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Is a language *L* expressive enough to axiomatize a single finite structure *S*?
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] However, these properties do not axiomatize the structure, since for structure (1') the above properties hold as well, yet structures (1) and (1') are not isomorphic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Informally the question is whether by adding enough properties, these properties together describe exactly (1) and are valid (all together) for no other structure (up to isomorphism).
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] For a single finite structure it is always possible to precisely describe the structure by a single FO sentence.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] The principle is illustrated here for a structure with one binary relation R and without constants.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] To this aim, we introduce first-order variables $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ that are interpreted as the n elements of the structure.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Finally, the structure is described by the FO sentence $\exists _{x_{1}}\dots \exists _{x_{n}}(\varphi _{1}\land \varphi _{2}\land \varphi _{3}\land \varphi _{4})$ .
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] The method of describing a single finite structure by means of a first-order sentence can easily be extended for any fixed number of structures.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] A unique description can be obtained by the disjunction of the descriptions for each structure.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] By definition, a set containing an infinite structure falls outside the area that FMT deals with.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Note that infinite structures can never be discriminated in FO, because of the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem, which implies that no first-order theory with an infinite model can have a unique model up to isomorphism.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] The most famous example is probably Skolem's theorem, that there is a countable non-standard model of arithmetic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Is a language *L* expressive enough to describe exactly (up to isomorphism) those finite structures that have certain property *P*?
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] The descriptions given so far all specify the number of elements of the universe.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Unfortunately most interesting sets of structures are not restricted to a certain size, like all graphs that are trees, are connected or are acyclic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Thus to discriminate a finite number of structures is of special importance.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Instead of a general statement, the following is a sketch of a methodology to differentiate between structures that can and cannot be discriminated.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] The methodology considers countably many subsets of the language, the union of which forms the language itself.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] For instance, for FO consider classes FO[*m*] for each *m*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] For each *m* the above core idea then has to be shown.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] That is: $A\in P,B\not \in P$ and $A\equiv _{m}B$ with a pair $A,B$ for each m and α (in ≡) from FO[*m*].
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] It may be appropriate to choose the classes FO[*m*] to form a partition of the language.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] One common way to define FO[*m*] is by means of the quantifier rank qr(α) of a FO formula α, which expresses the depth of quantifier nesting.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] For example, for a formula in prenex normal form, qr is simply the total number of its quantifiers.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Then FO[*m*] can be defined as all FO formulas α with qr(α) ≤ *m* (or, if a partition is desired, as those FO formulas with quantifier rank equal to *m*).
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Thus it all comes down to showing $A\models \alpha \Leftrightarrow B\models \alpha$ on the subsets FO[*m*].
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] The main approach here is to use the algebraic characterization provided by Ehrenfeucht–Fraïssé games.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Informally, these take a single partial isomorphism on *A* and *B* and extend it *m* times, in order to either prove or disprove $A\equiv _{m}B$ , dependent on who wins the game.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] We want to show that the property that the size of an ordered structure **A** = (A, ≤) is even, can not be expressed in FO.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] For *m* = 2, in a 2-move Ehrenfeucht–Fraïssé game on **A2** and **B2** the duplicator always wins, and thus **A2** and **B2** cannot be discriminated in FO[2], i.e. $\mathbf {A} _{2}\models \alpha \iff \mathbf {B} _{2}\models \alpha$ for every *α* ∈ FO[2].
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Next we have to scale the structures up by increasing *m*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] For example, for *m* = 3 we must find an **A3** and **B3** such that the duplicator always wins the 3-move game.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] More generally, we can choose A*m* = {1, ..., 2*m*} and B*m* = {1, ..., 2*m*−1}; for any *m* the duplicator always wins the *m*-move game for this pair of structures*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Thus EVEN on finite ordered structures cannot be expressed in FO.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] (1969) and, independently, Fagin (1976) proved a zero–one law for first-order sentences in finite models; Fagin's proof used the compactness theorem.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] According to this result, every first-order sentence in a relational signature $\sigma$ is either almost always true or almost always false in finite $\sigma$ -structures.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] That is, let S be a fixed first-order sentence, and choose a random $\sigma$ -structure $G_{n}$ with domain $\{1,\dots ,n\}$ , uniformly among all $\sigma$ -structures with domain $\{1,\dots ,n\}$ .
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] The problem of determining whether a given sentence has probability tending to zero or to one is PSPACE-complete.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] A similar analysis has been performed for more expressive logics than first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] The 0-1 law has been shown to hold for sentences in FO(LFP), first-order logic augmented with a least fixed point operator, and more generally for sentences in the infinitary logic $L_{\infty \omega }^{\omega }$ , which allows for potentially arbitrarily long conjunctions and disjunctions.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Another important variant is the unlabelled 0-1 law, where instead of considering the fraction of structures with domain $\{1,\dots ,n\}$ , one considers the fraction of isomorphism classes of structures with n elements.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] This fraction is well-defined, since any two isomorphic structures satisfy the same sentences.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] The unlabelled 0-1 law also holds for $L_{\infty \omega }^{\omega }$ and therefore in particular for FO(LFP) and first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] An important goal of finite model theory is the characterisation of complexity classes by the type of logic needed to express the languages in them.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] For example, PH, the union of all complexity classes in the polynomial hierarchy, is precisely the class of languages expressible by statements of second-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] This corresponds to a binary relation, say G(f, l) on FIRST_NAME × LAST_NAME.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Notice, we assume here, that all last names appear only once (or we should use SELECT DISTINCT since we assume that relations and answers are sets, not bags).
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Next we want to make a more complex statement.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Therefore, in addition to the "GIRLS" table we have a table "BOYS" also with the columns "FIRST_NAME" and "LAST_NAME".
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Now we want to query the names of all the girls that have the same last name as at least one of the boys.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Notice that in order to express the "∧" we introduced the new language element "IN" with a subsequent select statement.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] This makes the language more expressive for the price of higher difficulty to learn and implement.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] This is a common trade-off in formal language design.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] The way shown above ("IN") is by far not the only one to extend the language.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] First-order logic is too restrictive for some database applications, for instance because of its inability to express transitive closure.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] This has led to more powerful constructs being added to database query languages, such as recursive WITH in SQL:1999.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] More expressive logics, like fixpoint logics, have therefore been studied in finite model theory because of their relevance to database theory and applications.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Narrative data contains no defined relations.
[src:descriptive-complexity/finite-model-theory] Note that the challenges in full text search are different from database querying, like ranking of results.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] "Theory" is sometimes understood in a more formal sense as just a set of sentences in first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The term "first-order" distinguishes first-order logic from higher-order logic, in which there are predicates having predicates or functions as arguments, or in which quantification over predicates, functions, or both, are permitted.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] In first-order theories, predicates are often associated with sets.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] In interpreted higher-order theories, predicates may be interpreted as sets of sets.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] There are many deductive systems for first-order logic which are both sound, i.e. all provable statements are true in all models; and complete, i.e. all statements which are true in all models are provable.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Although the logical consequence relation is only semidecidable, much progress has been made in automated theorem proving in first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] First-order logic also satisfies several metalogical theorems that make it amenable to analysis in proof theory, such as the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem and the compactness theorem.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] First-order logic is the standard for the formalization of mathematics into axioms, and is studied in the foundations of mathematics.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Peano arithmetic and Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory are axiomatizations of number theory and set theory, respectively, into first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] No first-order theory, however, has the strength to uniquely describe a structure with an infinite domain, such as the natural numbers or the real line.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Axiom systems that do fully describe these two structures, i.e. categorical axiom systems, can be obtained in stronger logics such as second-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Historically speaking, the foundations of first-order logic were developed independently by Gottlob Frege and Charles Sanders Peirce in the 1880s.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] However, the distinction between first-order and higher-order logic was not well understood until metalogical ideas and results arrived, such as Gödel's completeness theorem in 1929.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] By the 1940s, first-order logic had become the dominant language of mathematical foundations.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] While propositional logic deals with simple declarative propositions, first-order logic additionally covers predicates and quantification.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] A predicate evaluates to true or false for an entity or entities in the domain of discourse.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Consider the two sentences "Socrates is a philosopher" and "Plato is a philosopher".
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] In propositional logic, these sentences themselves are viewed as the individuals of study, and might be denoted, for example, by variables such as *p* and *q*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] They are not viewed as an application of a predicate, such as ${\text{isPhilosopher}}$ , to any particular objects in the domain of discourse, instead viewing them as purely an utterance which is either true or false.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] However, in first-order logic, these two sentences may be framed as statements that a certain individual or non-logical object has a property.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] In this example, both sentences happen to have the common form ${\text{isPhilosopher}}(x)$ for some individual x , in the first sentence the value of the variable *x* is "Socrates", and in the second sentence it is "Plato".
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Due to the ability to speak about non-logical individuals along with the original logical connectives, first-order logic includes propositional logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The truth of a formula such as "*x* is a philosopher" depends on which object is denoted by *x* and on the interpretation of the predicate "is a philosopher".
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Consequently, "*x* is a philosopher" alone does not have a definite truth value of true or false, and is akin to a sentence fragment.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Relationships between predicates can be stated using logical connectives.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] For example, the first-order formula "if *x* is a philosopher, then *x* is a scholar", is a conditional statement with "*x* is a philosopher" as its hypothesis, and "*x* is a scholar" as its conclusion, which again needs specification of *x* in order to have a definite truth value.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Quantifiers can be applied to variables in a formula.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The variable *x* in the previous formula can be universally quantified, for instance, with the first-order sentence "For every *x*, if *x* is a philosopher, then *x* is a scholar".
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The universal quantifier "for every" in this sentence expresses the idea that the claim "if *x* is a philosopher, then *x* is a scholar" holds for *all* choices of *x*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The *negation* of the sentence "For every *x*, if *x* is a philosopher, then *x* is a scholar" is logically equivalent to the sentence "There exists *x* such that *x* is a philosopher and *x* is not a scholar".
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The existential quantifier "there exists" expresses the idea that the claim "*x* is a philosopher and *x* is not a scholar" holds for *some* choice of *x*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The predicates "is a philosopher" and "is a scholar" each take a single variable.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] In general, predicates can take several variables.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] In the first-order sentence "Socrates is the teacher of Plato", the predicate "is the teacher of" takes two variables.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] An interpretation (or model) of a first-order formula specifies what each predicate means, and the entities that can instantiate the variables.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] These entities form the domain of discourse or universe, which is usually required to be a nonempty set.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] There are two key parts of first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The syntax determines which finite sequences of symbols are well-formed expressions in first-order logic, while the semantics determines the meanings behind these expressions.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Unlike natural languages, such as English, the language of first-order logic is completely formal, so that it can be mechanically determined whether a given expression is well formed.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] There are two key types of well-formed expressions: *terms*, which intuitively represent objects, and *formulas*, which intuitively express statements that can be true or false.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The terms and formulas of first-order logic are strings of *symbols*, where all the symbols together form the *alphabet* of the language.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] As with all formal languages, the nature of the symbols themselves is outside the scope of formal logic; they are often regarded simply as letters and punctuation symbols.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] It is common to divide the symbols of the alphabet into *logical symbols*, which always have the same meaning, and *non-logical symbols*, whose meaning varies by interpretation.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] For example, the logical symbol $\land$ always represents "and"; it is never interpreted as "or", which is represented by the logical symbol $\lor$ .
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] However, a non-logical predicate symbol such as Phil(*x*) could be interpreted to mean "*x* is a philosopher", "*x* is a man named Philip", or any other unary predicate depending on the interpretation at hand.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Not all of these symbols are required in first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Either one of the quantifiers along with negation, conjunction (or disjunction), variables, brackets, and equality suffices.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Non-logical symbols represent predicates (relations), functions and constants.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] When the arity of a predicate symbol or function symbol is clear from context, the superscript *n* is often omitted.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] In this traditional approach, there is only one language of first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] This approach is still common, especially in philosophically oriented books.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] A more recent practice is to use different non-logical symbols according to the application one has in mind.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Therefore, it has become necessary to name the set of all non-logical symbols used in a particular application.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Typical signatures in mathematics are {1, ×} or just {×} for groups, or {0, 1, +, ×, <} for ordered fields.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] There are no restrictions on the number of non-logical symbols.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The signature can be empty, finite, or infinite, even uncountable.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Uncountable signatures occur for example in modern proofs of the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Though signatures might in some cases imply how non-logical symbols are to be interpreted, interpretation of the non-logical symbols in the signature is separate (and not necessarily fixed).
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Signatures concern syntax rather than semantics.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The traditional approach can be recovered in the modern approach, by simply specifying the "custom" signature to consist of the traditional sequences of non-logical symbols.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The formation rules define the terms and formulas of first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] When terms and formulas are represented as strings of symbols, these rules can be used to write a formal grammar for terms and formulas.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] These rules are generally context-free (each production has a single symbol on the left side), except that the set of symbols may be allowed to be infinite and there may be many start symbols, for example the variables in the case of terms.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] In particular, symbols denoting individual constants are nullary function symbols, and thus are terms.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Only expressions which can be obtained by finitely many applications of rules 1 and 2 are terms.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] For example, no expression involving a predicate symbol is a term.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] If $\varphi$ is a formula, then $\lnot \varphi$ is a formula.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] If ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\psi$ ⁠ are formulas, then ( $\varphi \rightarrow \psi$ ) is a formula.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Similar rules apply to other binary logical connectives.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] If $\varphi$ is a formula and *x* is a variable, then $\forall x\varphi$ (for all x, $\varphi$ holds) and $\exists x\varphi$ (there exists x such that $\varphi$ ) are formulas.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Only expressions which can be obtained by finitely many applications of rules 1–4 are formulas.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The formulas obtained from the first rule are said to be *atomic formulas*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] is a formula, if *f* is a unary function symbol, *P* a unary predicate symbol, and Q a ternary predicate symbol.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] However, $\forall x\,x\rightarrow$ is not a formula, although it is a string of symbols from the alphabet.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The role of the parentheses in the definition is to ensure that any formula can only be obtained in one way—by following the inductive definition (i.e., there is a unique parse tree for each formula).
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] This property is known as *unique readability* of formulas.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] There are many conventions for where parentheses are used in formulas.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] For example, some authors use colons or full stops instead of parentheses, or change the places in which parentheses are inserted.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Each author's particular definition must be accompanied by a proof of unique readability.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] For convenience, conventions have been developed about the precedence of the logical operators, to avoid the need to write parentheses in some cases.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] These rules are similar to the order of operations in arithmetic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Moreover, extra punctuation not required by the definition may be inserted—to make formulas easier to read.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] In a formula, a variable may occur *free* or *bound* (or both).
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] One formalization of this notion is due to Quine, first the concept of a variable occurrence is defined, then whether a variable occurrence is free or bound, then whether a variable symbol overall is free or bound.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] In order to distinguish different occurrences of the identical symbol *x*, each occurrence of a variable symbol *x* in a formula φ is identified with the initial substring of φ up to the point at which said instance of the symbol *x* appears.p.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] 297 Then, an occurrence of *x* is said to be bound if that occurrence of *x* lies within the scope of at least one of either $\exists x$ or $\forall x$ .
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Finally, *x* is bound in φ if all occurrences of *x* in φ are bound.pp.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Intuitively, a variable symbol is free in a formula if at no point is it quantified:pp.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] 142–143 in ∀*y* *P*(*x*, *y*), the sole occurrence of variable *x* is free while that of *y* is bound.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The free and bound variable occurrences in a formula are defined inductively as follows.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Moreover, there are no bound variables in any atomic formula.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The same rule applies to any other binary connective in place of →.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] For example, in ∀*x* ∀*y* (*P*(*x*) → *Q*(*x*,*f*(*x*),*z*)), *x* and *y* occur only bound, *z* occurs only free, and *w* is neither because it does not occur in the formula.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Free and bound variables of a formula need not be disjoint sets: in the formula *P*(*x*) → ∀*x* *Q*(*x*), the first occurrence of *x*, as argument of *P*, is free while the second one, as argument of *Q*, is bound.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] A formula in first-order logic with no free variable occurrences is called a *first-order sentence*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] These are the formulas that will have well-defined truth values under an interpretation.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] For example, whether a formula such as Phil(*x*) is true must depend on what *x* represents.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] But the sentence ∃*x* Phil(*x*) will be either true or false in a given interpretation.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] In mathematics, the language of ordered abelian groups has one constant symbol 0, one unary function symbol −, one binary function symbol +, and one binary relation symbol ≤.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The axioms for ordered abelian groups can be expressed as a set of sentences in the language.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] An interpretation of a first-order language assigns a denotation to each non-logical symbol (predicate symbol, function symbol, or constant symbol) in that language.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] It also determines a domain of discourse that specifies the range of the quantifiers.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The result is that each term is assigned an object that it represents, each predicate is assigned a property of objects, and each sentence is assigned a truth value.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] In this way, an interpretation provides semantic meaning to the terms, predicates, and formulas of the language.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The study of the interpretations of formal languages is called formal semantics.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] What follows is a description of the standard or Tarskian semantics for first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The most common way of specifying an interpretation (especially in mathematics) is to specify a *structure* (also called a *model*; see below).
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The structure consists of a domain of discourse *D* and an interpretation function I mapping non-logical symbols to predicates, functions, and constants.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The domain of discourse *D* is a nonempty set of "objects" of some kind.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] For example, one can take *D* to be the set of integers.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] A formula evaluates to true or false given an interpretation and a **variable assignment** μ that associates an element of the domain of discourse with each variable.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The reason that a variable assignment is required is to give meanings to formulas with free variables, such as $y=x$ .
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The truth value of this formula changes depending on the values that *x* and *y* denote.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] First, the variable assignment μ can be extended to all terms of the language, with the result that each term maps to a single element of the domain of discourse.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Next, each formula is assigned a truth value.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The inductive definition used to make this assignment is called the T-schema.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] If a formula does not contain free variables, and thus is a sentence, then the initial variable assignment does not affect its truth value.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] In other words, a sentence is true according to *M* and $\mu$ if and only if it is true according to *M* and every other variable assignment $\mu '$ .
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] There is a second common approach to defining truth values that does not rely on variable assignment functions.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Instead, given an interpretation *M*, one first adds to the signature a collection of constant symbols, one for each element of the domain of discourse in *M*; say that for each *d* in the domain the constant symbol *c**d* is fixed.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The interpretation is extended so that each new constant symbol is assigned to its corresponding element of the domain.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] This alternate approach gives exactly the same truth values to all sentences as the approach via variable assignments.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] If a sentence φ evaluates to *true* under a given interpretation *M*, one says that *M* *satisfies* φ; this is denoted $M\vDash \varphi$ .
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] A sentence is *satisfiable* if there is some interpretation under which it is true.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] This is a bit different from the symbol $\vDash$ from model theory, where $M\vDash \phi$ denotes satisfiability in a model, i.e.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] "there is a suitable assignment of values in M 's domain to variable symbols of $\phi$ ".
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Satisfiability of formulas with free variables is more complicated, because an interpretation on its own does not determine the truth value of such a formula.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The most common convention is that a formula φ with free variables $x_{1}$ , ..., $x_{n}$ is said to be satisfied by an interpretation if the formula φ remains true regardless which individuals from the domain of discourse are assigned to its free variables $x_{1}$ , ..., $x_{n}$ .
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] This has the same effect as saying that a formula φ is satisfied if and only if its universal closure $\forall x_{1}\dots \forall x_{n}\phi (x_{1},\dots ,x_{n})$ is satisfied.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] A formula is *logically valid* (or simply *valid*) if it is true in every interpretation.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] These formulas play a role similar to tautologies in propositional logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] A formula φ is a *logical consequence* of a formula ψ if every interpretation that makes ψ true also makes φ true.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] In this case one says that φ is logically implied by ψ.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] An alternate approach to the semantics of first-order logic proceeds via abstract algebra.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] This approach generalizes the Lindenbaum–Tarski algebras of propositional logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] These algebras are all lattices that properly extend the two-element Boolean algebra.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Tarski and Givant (1987) showed that the fragment of first-order logic that has no atomic sentence lying in the scope of more than three quantifiers has the same expressive power as relation algebra.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] This fragment is of great interest because it suffices for Peano arithmetic and most axiomatic set theory, including the canonical Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory (ZFC).
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] They also prove that first-order logic with a primitive ordered pair is equivalent to a relation algebra with two ordered pair projection functions.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] A *first-order theory* of a particular signature is a set of axioms, which are sentences consisting of symbols from that signature.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The set of axioms is often finite or recursively enumerable, in which case the theory is called *effective*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Some authors require theories to also include all logical consequences of the axioms.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The axioms are considered to hold within the theory and from them other sentences that hold within the theory can be derived.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] A first-order structure that satisfies all sentences in a given theory is said to be a *model* of the theory.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] An *elementary class* is the set of all structures satisfying a particular theory.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] These classes are a main subject of study in model theory.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Many theories have an *intended interpretation*, a certain model that is kept in mind when studying the theory.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] For example, the intended interpretation of Peano arithmetic consists of the usual natural numbers with their usual operations.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] However, the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem shows that most first-order theories will also have other, nonstandard models.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] A theory is *consistent* (within a deductive system) if it is not possible to prove a contradiction from the axioms of the theory.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] A theory is *complete* if, for every formula in its signature, either that formula or its negation is a logical consequence of the axioms of the theory.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Gödel's incompleteness theorem shows that effective first-order theories that include a sufficient portion of the arithmetic of the natural numbers can never be both consistent and complete.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The definition above requires that the domain of discourse of any interpretation must be nonempty.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] There are settings, such as inclusive logic, where empty domains are permitted.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Moreover, if a class of algebraic structures includes an empty structure (for example, there is an empty poset), that class can only be an elementary class in first-order logic if empty domains are permitted or the empty structure is removed from the class.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Thus, when the empty domain is permitted, it must often be treated as a special case.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Most authors, however, simply exclude the empty domain by definition.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] A *deductive system* is used to demonstrate, on a purely syntactic basis, that one formula is a logical consequence of another formula.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] There are many such systems for first-order logic, including Hilbert-style deductive systems, natural deduction, the sequent calculus, the tableaux method, and resolution.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] These share the common property that a deduction is a finite syntactic object; the format of this object, and the way it is constructed, vary widely.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] These finite deductions themselves are often called *derivations* in proof theory.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] They are also often called *proofs* but are completely formalized unlike natural-language mathematical proofs.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] A deductive system is *sound* if any formula that can be derived in the system is logically valid.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Conversely, a deductive system is *complete* if every logically valid formula is derivable.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] All of the systems discussed in this article are both sound and complete.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] They also share the property that it is possible to effectively verify that a purportedly valid deduction is actually a deduction; such deduction systems are called *effective*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] A key property of deductive systems is that they are purely syntactic, so that derivations can be verified without considering any interpretation.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Thus, a sound argument is correct in every possible interpretation of the language, regardless of whether that interpretation is about mathematics, economics, or some other area.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] In general, logical consequence in first-order logic is only semidecidable: if a sentence A logically implies a sentence B then this can be discovered (for example, by searching for a proof until one is found, using some effective, sound, complete proof system).
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] However, if A does not logically imply B, this does not mean that A logically implies the negation of B.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] There is no effective procedure that, given formulas A and B, always correctly decides whether A logically implies B.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] A *rule of inference* states that, given a particular formula (or set of formulas) with a certain property as a hypothesis, another specific formula (or set of formulas) can be derived as a conclusion.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The rule is sound (or truth-preserving) if it preserves validity in the sense that whenever any interpretation satisfies the hypothesis, that interpretation also satisfies the conclusion.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] For example, one common rule of inference is the *rule of substitution*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] If *t* is a term and φ is a formula possibly containing the variable *x*, then φ[*t*/*x*] is the result of replacing all free instances of *x* by *t* in φ.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The substitution rule states that for any φ and any term *t*, one can conclude φ[*t*/*x*] from φ provided that no free variable of *t* becomes bound during the substitution process.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] To see why the restriction on bound variables is necessary, consider the logically valid formula φ given by $\exists x(x=y)$ , in the signature of (0,1,+,×,=) of arithmetic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] If *t* is the term "x + 1", the formula φ[*t*/*y*] is $\exists x(x=x+1)$ , which will be false in many interpretations.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The problem is that the free variable *x* of *t* became bound during the substitution.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The intended replacement can be obtained by renaming the bound variable *x* of φ to something else, say *z*, so that the formula after substitution is $\exists z(z=x+1)$ , which is again logically valid.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The substitution rule demonstrates several common aspects of rules of inference.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] It is entirely syntactical; one can tell whether it was correctly applied without appeal to any interpretation.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] It has (syntactically defined) limitations on when it can be applied, which must be respected to preserve the correctness of derivations.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Moreover, as is often the case, these limitations are necessary because of interactions between free and bound variables that occur during syntactic manipulations of the formulas involved in the inference rule.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] A deduction in a Hilbert-style deductive system is a list of formulas, each of which is a *logical axiom*, a hypothesis that has been assumed for the derivation at hand or follows from previous formulas via a rule of inference.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The logical axioms consist of several axiom schemas of logically valid formulas; these encompass a significant amount of propositional logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The rules of inference enable the manipulation of quantifiers.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Typical Hilbert-style systems have a small number of rules of inference, along with several infinite schemas of logical axioms.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] It is common to have only modus ponens and universal generalization as rules of inference.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Natural deduction systems resemble Hilbert-style systems in that a deduction is a finite list of formulas.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] However, natural deduction systems have no logical axioms; they compensate by adding additional rules of inference that can be used to manipulate the logical connectives in formulas in the proof.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The sequent calculus was developed to study the properties of natural deduction systems.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] where A1, ..., A*n*, B1, ..., B*k* are formulas and the turnstile symbol $\vdash$ is used as punctuation to separate the two halves.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Intuitively, a sequent expresses the idea that $(A_{1}\land \cdots \land A_{n})$ implies $(B_{1}\lor \cdots \lor B_{k})$ .
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Unlike the methods just described the derivations in the tableaux method are not lists of formulas.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Instead, a derivation is a tree of formulas.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] To show that a formula A is provable, the tableaux method attempts to demonstrate that the negation of A is unsatisfiable.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The tree of the derivation has $\lnot A$ at its root; the tree branches in a way that reflects the structure of the formula.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] For example, to show that $C\lor D$ is unsatisfiable requires showing that C and D are each unsatisfiable; this corresponds to a branching point in the tree with parent $C\lor D$ and children C and D.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The resolution rule is a single rule of inference that, together with unification, is sound and complete for first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] As with the tableaux method, a formula is proved by showing that the negation of the formula is unsatisfiable.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Resolution is commonly used in automated theorem proving.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The resolution method works only with formulas that are disjunctions of atomic formulas; arbitrary formulas must first be converted to this form through Skolemization.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The resolution rule states that from the hypotheses $A_{1}\lor \cdots \lor A_{k}\lor C$ and $B_{1}\lor \cdots \lor B_{l}\lor \lnot C$ , the conclusion $A_{1}\lor \cdots \lor A_{k}\lor B_{1}\lor \cdots \lor B_{l}$ can be obtained.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] Many identities can be proved, which establish equivalences between particular formulas.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] These identities allow for rearranging formulas by moving quantifiers across other connectives and are useful for putting formulas in prenex normal form.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] There are several different conventions for using equality (or identity) in first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The most common convention, known as **first-order logic with equality**, includes the equality symbol as a primitive logical symbol which is always interpreted as the real equality relation between members of the domain of discourse, such that the "two" given members are the same member.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] This approach also adds certain axioms about equality to the deductive system employed.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] These are axiom schemas, each of which specifies an infinite set of axioms.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The third schema is known as *Leibniz's law*, "the principle of substitutivity", "the indiscernibility of identicals", or "the replacement property".
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] An alternate approach considers the equality relation to be a non-logical symbol.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] This convention is known as *first-order logic without equality*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] If an equality relation is included in the signature, the axioms of equality must now be added to the theories under consideration, if desired, instead of being considered rules of logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The main difference between this method and first-order logic with equality is that an interpretation may now interpret two distinct individuals as "equal" (although, by Leibniz's law, these will satisfy exactly the same formulas under any interpretation).
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] That is, the equality relation may now be interpreted by an arbitrary equivalence relation on the domain of discourse that is congruent with respect to the functions and relations of the interpretation.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] When this second convention is followed, the term *normal model* is used to refer to an interpretation where no distinct individuals *a* and *b* satisfy *a* = *b*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] In first-order logic with equality, only normal models are considered, and so there is no term for a model other than a normal model.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] When first-order logic without equality is studied, it is necessary to amend the statements of results such as the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem so that only normal models are considered.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] First-order logic without equality is often employed in the context of second-order arithmetic and other higher-order theories of arithmetic, where the equality relation between sets of natural numbers is usually omitted.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] If a theory has a binary formula *A*(*x*,*y*) which satisfies reflexivity and Leibniz's law, the theory is said to have equality, or to be a theory with equality.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] The theory may not have all instances of the above schemas as axioms, but rather as derivable theorems.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p01] For example, in theories with no function symbols and a finite number of relations, it is possible to define equality in terms of the relations, by defining the two terms *s* and *t* to be equal if any relation is unchanged by changing *s* to *t* in any argument.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] One motivation for the use of first-order logic, rather than higher-order logic, is that first-order logic has many metalogical properties that stronger logics do not have.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] These results concern general properties of first-order logic itself, rather than properties of individual theories.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] They provide fundamental tools for the construction of models of first-order theories.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Gödel's completeness theorem, proved by Kurt Gödel in 1929, establishes that there are sound, complete, effective deductive systems for first-order logic, and thus the first-order logical consequence relation is captured by finite provability.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Naively, the statement that a formula φ logically implies a formula ψ depends on every model of φ; these models will in general be of arbitrarily large cardinality, and so logical consequence cannot be effectively verified by checking every model.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] However, it is possible to enumerate all finite derivations and search for a derivation of ψ from φ.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] If ψ is logically implied by φ, such a derivation will eventually be found.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Thus first-order logical consequence is semidecidable: it is possible to make an effective enumeration of all pairs of sentences (φ,ψ) such that ψ is a logical consequence of φ.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Unlike propositional logic, first-order logic is undecidable (although semidecidable), provided that the language has at least one predicate of arity at least 2 (other than equality).
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] This means that there is no decision procedure that determines whether arbitrary formulas are logically valid.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] This result was established independently by Alonzo Church and Alan Turing in 1936 and 1937, respectively, giving a negative answer to the Entscheidungsproblem posed by David Hilbert and Wilhelm Ackermann in 1928.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Their proofs demonstrate a connection between the unsolvability of the decision problem for first-order logic and the unsolvability of the halting problem.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] There are systems weaker than full first-order logic for which the logical consequence relation is decidable.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] These include propositional logic and monadic predicate logic, which is first-order logic restricted to unary predicate symbols and no function symbols.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Other logics with no function symbols which are decidable are the guarded fragment of first-order logic, as well as two-variable logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] The Bernays–Schönfinkel class of first-order formulas is also decidable.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Decidable subsets of first-order logic are also studied in the framework of description logics.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] See (Pratt-Hartmann, 2023) for a monograph.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] The Löwenheim–Skolem theorem shows that if a first-order theory of cardinality λ has an infinite model, then it has models of every infinite cardinality greater than or equal to λ.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] One of the earliest results in model theory, it implies that it is not possible to characterize countability or uncountability in a first-order language with a countable signature.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] That is, there is no first-order formula φ(*x*) such that an arbitrary structure M satisfies φ if and only if the domain of discourse of M is countable (or, in the second case, uncountable).
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] The Löwenheim–Skolem theorem implies that infinite structures cannot be categorically axiomatized in first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] For example, there is no first-order theory whose only model is the real line: any first-order theory with an infinite model also has a model of cardinality larger than the continuum.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Since the real line is infinite, any theory satisfied by the real line is also satisfied by some nonstandard models.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] When the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem is applied to first-order set theories, the nonintuitive consequences are known as Skolem's paradox.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] The compactness theorem states that a set of first-order sentences has a model if and only if every finite subset of it has a model.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] This implies that if a formula is a logical consequence of an infinite set of first-order axioms, then it is a logical consequence of some finite number of those axioms.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] This theorem was proved first by Kurt Gödel as a consequence of the completeness theorem, but many additional proofs have been obtained over time.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] It is a central tool in model theory, providing a fundamental method for constructing models.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] The compactness theorem has a limiting effect on which collections of first-order structures are elementary classes.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] For example, the compactness theorem implies that any theory that has arbitrarily large finite models has an infinite model.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Thus, the class of all finite graphs is not an elementary class (the same holds for many other algebraic structures).
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] There are also more subtle limitations of first-order logic that are implied by the compactness theorem.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] For example, in computer science, many situations can be modeled as a directed graph of states (nodes) and connections (directed edges).
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Validating such a system may require showing that no "bad" state can be reached from any "good" state.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Thus, one seeks to determine if the good and bad states are in different connected components of the graph.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] However, the compactness theorem can be used to show that connected graphs are not an elementary class in first-order logic, and there is no formula φ(*x*,*y*) of first-order logic, in the logic of graphs, that expresses the idea that there is a path from *x* to *y*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Connectedness can be expressed in second-order logic, however, but not with only existential set quantifiers, as $\Sigma _{1}^{1}$ also enjoys compactness.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Per Lindström showed that the metalogical properties just discussed actually characterize first-order logic in the sense that no stronger logic can also have those properties (Ebbinghaus and Flum 1994, Chapter XIII).
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Lindström defined a class of abstract logical systems, and a rigorous definition of the relative strength of a member of this class.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Although first-order logic is sufficient for formalizing much of mathematics and is commonly used in computer science and other fields, it has certain limitations.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] These include limitations on its expressiveness and limitations of the fragments of natural languages that it can describe.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] The Löwenheim–Skolem theorem shows that if a first-order theory has any infinite model, then it has infinite models of every cardinality.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] In particular, no first-order theory with an infinite model can be categorical.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Thus, there is no first-order theory whose only model has the set of natural numbers as its domain, or whose only model has the set of real numbers as its domain.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Many extensions of first-order logic, including infinitary logics and higher-order logics, are more expressive in the sense that they do permit categorical axiomatizations of the natural numbers or real numbers.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] This expressiveness comes at a metalogical cost, however: by Lindström's theorem, the compactness theorem and the downward Löwenheim–Skolem theorem cannot hold in any logic stronger than first-order.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] First-order logic is able to formalize many simple quantifier constructions in natural language, such as "every person who lives in Perth lives in Australia".
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Hence, first-order logic is used as a basis for knowledge representation languages, such as FO(.).
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Still, there are complicated features of natural language that cannot be expressed in first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] "Any logical system which is appropriate as an instrument for the analysis of natural language needs a much richer structure than first-order predicate logic".
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] There are many variations of first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Some of these are inessential in the sense that they merely change notation without affecting the semantics.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Others change the expressive power more significantly, by extending the semantics through additional quantifiers or other new logical symbols.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] For example, infinitary logics permit formulas of infinite size, and modal logics add symbols for possibility and necessity.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Restrictions such as these are useful as a technique to reduce the number of inference rules or axiom schemas in deductive systems, which leads to shorter proofs of metalogical results.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Similarly, derivations in the limited systems may be longer than derivations in systems that include additional connectives.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] There is thus a trade-off between the ease of working within the formal system and the ease of proving results about the formal system.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] It is also possible to restrict the arities of function symbols and predicate symbols, in sufficiently expressive theories.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] One can in principle dispense entirely with functions of arity greater than 2 and predicates of arity greater than 1 in theories that include a pairing function.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] This is a function of arity 2 that takes pairs of elements of the domain and returns an ordered pair containing them.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] It is also sufficient to have two predicate symbols of arity 2 that define projection functions from an ordered pair to its components.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] In either case it is necessary that the natural axioms for a pairing function and its projections are satisfied.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Ordinary first-order interpretations have a single domain of discourse over which all quantifiers range.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] *Many-sorted first-order logic* allows variables to have different *sorts*, which have different domains.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] This is also called *typed first-order logic*, and the sorts called *types* (as in data type), but it is not the same as first-order type theory.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Many-sorted first-order logic is often used in the study of second-order arithmetic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] When there are only finitely many sorts in a theory, many-sorted first-order logic can be reduced to single-sorted first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] One introduces into the single-sorted theory a unary predicate symbol for each sort in the many-sorted theory and adds an axiom saying that these unary predicates partition the domain of discourse.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Then the elements satisfying $P_{1}$ are thought of as elements of the first sort, and elements satisfying $P_{2}$ as elements of the second sort.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] One can quantify over each sort by using the corresponding predicate symbol to limit the range of quantification.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Additional quantifiers can be added to first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Infinitary logic allows infinitely long sentences.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] For example, one may allow a conjunction or disjunction of infinitely many formulas, or quantification over infinitely many variables.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Infinitely long sentences arise in areas of mathematics including topology and model theory.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Infinitary logic generalizes first-order logic to allow formulas of infinite length.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] The most common way in which formulas can become infinite is through infinite conjunctions and disjunctions.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] However, it is also possible to admit generalized signatures in which function and relation symbols are allowed to have infinite arities, or in which quantifiers can bind infinitely many variables.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Because an infinite formula cannot be represented by a finite string, it is necessary to choose some other representation of formulas; the usual representation in this context is a tree.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Thus, formulas are, essentially, identified with their parse trees, rather than with the strings being parsed.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] The most commonly studied infinitary logics are denoted *L*αβ, where α and β are each either cardinal numbers or the symbol ∞.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] In this notation, ordinary first-order logic is *L*ωω.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] In the logic *L*∞ω, arbitrary conjunctions or disjunctions are allowed when building formulas, and there is an unlimited supply of variables.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] More generally, the logic that permits conjunctions or disjunctions with less than κ constituents is known as *L*κω.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] For example, *L*ω1ω permits countable conjunctions and disjunctions.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] The set of free variables in a formula of *L*κω can have any cardinality strictly less than κ, yet only finitely many of them can be in the scope of any quantifier when a formula appears as a subformula of another.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] In other infinitary logics, a subformula may be in the scope of infinitely many quantifiers.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] For example, in *L*κ∞, a single universal or existential quantifier may bind arbitrarily many variables simultaneously.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Similarly, the logic *L*κλ permits simultaneous quantification over fewer than λ variables, as well as conjunctions and disjunctions of size less than κ.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Fixpoint logic extends first-order logic by adding the closure under the least fixed points of positive operators.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] The characteristic feature of first-order logic is that individuals can be quantified, but not predicates.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] is not, in most formalizations of first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Second-order logic extends first-order logic by adding the latter type of quantification.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Other higher-order logics allow quantification over even higher types than second-order logic permits.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] These higher types include relations between relations, functions from relations to relations between relations, and other higher-type objects.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Thus the "first" in first-order logic describes the type of objects that can be quantified.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Unlike first-order logic, for which only one semantics is studied, there are several possible semantics for second-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] The most commonly employed semantics for second-order and higher-order logic is known as *full semantics*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] The combination of additional quantifiers and the full semantics for these quantifiers makes higher-order logic stronger than first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] In particular, the (semantic) logical consequence relation for second-order and higher-order logic is not semidecidable; there is no effective deduction system for second-order logic that is sound and complete under full semantics.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Second-order logic with full semantics is more expressive than first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] For example, it is possible to create axiom systems in second-order logic that uniquely characterize the natural numbers and the real line.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] The cost of this expressiveness is that second-order and higher-order logics have fewer attractive metalogical properties than first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] For example, the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem and compactness theorem of first-order logic become false when generalized to higher-order logics with full semantics.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Automated theorem proving refers to the development of computer programs that search and find derivations (formal proofs) of mathematical theorems.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Finding derivations is a difficult task because the search space can be very large; an exhaustive search of every possible derivation is theoretically possible but computationally infeasible for many systems of interest in mathematics.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Thus complicated heuristic functions are developed to attempt to find a derivation in less time than a blind search.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] The related area of automated proof verification uses computer programs to check that human-created proofs are correct.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Unlike complicated automated theorem provers, verification systems may be small enough that their correctness can be checked both by hand and through automated software verification.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] This validation of the proof verifier is needed to give confidence that any derivation labeled as "correct" is actually correct.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Some proof verifiers, such as Metamath, insist on having a complete derivation as input.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Others, such as Mizar and Isabelle, take a well-formatted proof sketch (which may still be very long and detailed) and fill in the missing pieces by doing simple proof searches or applying known decision procedures: the resulting derivation is then verified by a small core "kernel".
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Many such systems are primarily intended for interactive use by human mathematicians: these are known as proof assistants.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] They may also use formal logics that are stronger than first-order logic, such as type theory.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Because a full derivation of any nontrivial result in a first-order deductive system will be extremely long for a human to write, results are often formalized as a series of lemmas, for which derivations can be constructed separately.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Automated theorem provers are also used to implement formal verification in computer science.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] In this setting, theorem provers are used to verify the correctness of programs and of hardware such as processors with respect to a formal specification.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] Because such analysis is time-consuming and thus expensive, it is usually reserved for projects in which a malfunction would have grave human or financial consequences.
[src:descriptive-complexity/first-order-logic-p02] For the problem of model checking, efficient algorithms are known to decide whether an input finite structure satisfies a first-order formula, in addition to computational complexity bounds: see Model checking § First-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] In computational complexity theory, the **Immerman–Szelepcsényi theorem** states that nondeterministic space complexity classes are closed under complementation.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] It was proven independently by Neil Immerman and Róbert Szelepcsényi in 1987, for which they shared the 1995 Gödel Prize.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] In its general form the theorem states that NSPACE(*s*(*n*)) = co-NSPACE(*s*(*n*)) for any function *s*(*n*) ≥ log *n*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] The result is equivalently stated as NL = co-NL; although this is the special case when *s*(*n*) = log *n*, it implies the general theorem by a standard padding argument.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] The result solved the second LBA problem.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] In other words, if a nondeterministic machine can solve a problem, another machine with the same resource bounds can solve its complement problem (with the *yes* and *no* answers reversed) in the same asymptotic amount of space.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] No similar result is known for the time complexity classes, and indeed it is conjectured that NP is not equal to co-NP.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] The principle used to prove the theorem has become known as inductive counting.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] It has also been used to prove other theorems in computational complexity, including the closure of LOGCFL under complementation and the existence of error-free randomized logspace algorithms for USTCON.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] The theorem is obtained from this special case by a padding argument.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] The st-connectivity problem asks, given a digraph *G* and two vertices *s* and *t*, whether there is a directed path from *s* to *t* in *G*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] This problem is NL-complete, therefore its complement *st-non-connectivity* is co-NL-complete.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] It suffices to show that *st-non-connectivity* is in NL.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] This proves co-NL ⊆ NL, and by complementation, NL ⊆ co-NL.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] We fix a digraph *G*, a source vertex *s*, and a target vertex *t*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] We denote by *R**k* the set of vertices which are reachable from *s* in at most *k* steps.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] Note that if *t* is reachable from *s*, it is reachable in at most *n-1* steps, where *n* is the number of vertices, therefore we are reduced to testing whether *t* ∉ *R**n-1*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] We remark that *R*0 = { *s* }, and *R**k*+1 is the set of vertices *v* which are either in *R**k*, or the target of an edge *w* → *v* where *w* is in *R**k*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] This immediately gives an algorithm to decide *t* ∈ *R**n*, by successively computing *R**1*, …, *R**n*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] However, this algorithm uses too much space to solve the problem in NL, since storing a set *R**k* requires one bit per vertex.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] The crucial idea of the proof is that instead of computing *R**k*+1 from *R**k*, it is possible to compute the *size* of *R**k*+1 from the *size* of *R**k*, with the help of non-determinism.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] We iterate over vertices and increment a counter for each vertex that is found to belong to *R**k*+1.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] The problem is how to determine whether *v* ∈ *R**k*+1 for a given vertex *v*, when we only have the size of *R**k* available.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] To this end, we iterate over vertices *w*, and for each *w*, we non-deterministically *guess* whether *w* ∈ *R**k*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] If we guess *w* ∈ *R**k*, and *v* = *w* or there is an edge *w* → *v*, then we determine that *v* belongs to *R**k*+1.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] If this fails for all vertices *w*, then *v* does not belong to *R**k*+1.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] Thus, the computation that determines whether *v* belongs to *R**k*+1 splits into branches for the different guesses of which vertices belong to *R**k*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] A mechanism is needed to make all of these branches abort (reject immediately), except the one where all the guesses were correct.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] For this, when we have made a “yes-guess” that *w* ∈ *R**k*, we *check* this guess, by non-deterministically looking for a path from *s* to *w* of length at most *k*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] If this check fails, we abort the current branch.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] If it succeeds, we increment a counter of “yes-guesses”.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] On the other hand, we do not check the “no-guesses” that *w* ∉ *R**k* (this would require solving *st-non-connectivity*, which is precisely the problem that we are solving in the first place).
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] However, at the end of the loop over *w*, we check that the counter of “yes-guesses” matches the size of *R**k*, which we know.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] Otherwise, all the “yes-guesses” were correct, and there was exactly the right number of them, thus all “no-guesses” were correct as well.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] This concludes the computation of the size of *R**k*+1 from the size of *R**k*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] Finally, we check whether *t* ∈ *R**n-1*, which is possible from the size of *R**n*-2 by the sub-algorithm that is used inside the computation of the size of *R**k*+1.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] In logic and mathematics, **second-order logic** is an extension of first-order logic, which itself is an extension of propositional logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Second-order logic is in turn extended by higher-order logic and type theory.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] First-order logic quantifies only variables that range over individuals (elements of the domain of discourse); second-order logic, in addition, quantifies over relations.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] For example, the second-order sentence $\forall P\,\forall x(Px\lor \neg Px)$ says that for every formula *P*, and every individual *x*, either *Px* is true or not(*Px*) is true (this is the law of excluded middle).
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Second-order logic also includes quantification over sets, functions, and other variables (see section below).
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Both first-order and second-order logic use the idea of a domain of discourse (often called simply the "domain" or the "universe").
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] The domain is a set over which individual elements may be quantified.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] First-order logic can quantify over individuals, but not over properties.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] However, we cannot do the same with the predicate.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] is not a sentence of first-order logic, but this is a legitimate sentence of second-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Here, *P* is a predicate variable and is semantically a set of individuals.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] As a result, second-order logic has greater expressive power than first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] For example, there is no way in first-order logic to identify the set of all cubes and tetrahedrons.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] We can then assert properties of this set.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Second-order quantification is especially useful because it gives the ability to express reachability properties.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] For example, if Parent(*x*, *y*) denotes that *x* is a parent of *y*, then first-order logic cannot express the property that *x* is an ancestor of *y*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] It is notable that while we have variables for predicates in second-order logic, we don't have variables for properties of predicates.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] We cannot say, for example, that there is a property Shape(*P*) that is true for the predicates *P* Cube, Tet, and Dodec.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Objects are defined to be equal when they share all properties.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] In first-order logic, the induction axiom of Peano arithmetic is actually stated as a schema for generating an infinite collection of first-order axioms.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] The syntax of second-order logic prescribes which expressions are well formed formulas.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] In addition to the syntax of first-order logic, second-order logic includes many new *sorts* (sometimes called *types*) of variables.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Each of the variables just defined may be universally and/or existentially quantified over, to build up formulas.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Thus there are many kinds of quantifiers, two for each sort of variables.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] A *sentence* in second-order logic, as in first-order logic, is a well-formed formula with no free variables (of any sort).
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Just as in first-order logic, second-order logic may include non-logical symbols in a particular second-order language.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] These are restricted, however, in that all terms that they form must be either first-order terms (which can be substituted for a first-order variable) or second-order terms (which can be substituted for a second-order variable of an appropriate sort).
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] A formula in second-order logic is said to be of first-order (and sometimes denoted $\Sigma _{0}^{1}$ or $\Pi _{0}^{1}$ ) if its quantifiers (which may be universal or existential) range only over variables of first order, although it may have free variables of second order.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] A $\Sigma _{1}^{1}$ (existential second-order) formula is one additionally having some existential quantifiers over second-order variables, i.e. $\exists R_{0}\ldots \exists R_{m}\phi$ , where $\phi$ is a first-order formula.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] The fragment of second-order logic consisting only of existential second-order formulas is called **existential second-order logic** and abbreviated as ESO, as $\Sigma _{1}^{1}$ , or even as ∃SO.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] The fragment of $\Pi _{1}^{1}$ formulas is defined dually, it is called universal second-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] The semantics of second-order logic establish the meaning of each sentence.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Unlike first-order logic, which has only one standard semantics, there are two different semantics that are commonly used for second-order logic: **standard semantics** and **Henkin semantics**.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] In each of these semantics, the interpretations of the first-order quantifiers and the logical connectives are the same as in first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Only the ranges of quantifiers over second-order variables differ in the two types of semantics.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] In standard semantics, also called full semantics, the quantifiers range over *all* sets or functions of the appropriate sort.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] A model with this condition is called a full model, and these are the same as models in which the range of the second-order quantifiers is the powerset of the model's first-order part.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Thus once the domain of the first-order variables is established, the meaning of the remaining quantifiers is fixed.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] It is these semantics that give second-order logic its expressive power, and they will be assumed for the remainder of this article.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Leon Henkin (1950) defined an alternative kind of semantics for second-order and higher-order theories, in which the meaning of the higher-order domains is partly determined by an explicit axiomatisation, drawing on type theory, of the properties of the sets or functions ranged over.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Henkin semantics is a kind of many-sorted first-order semantics, where there are a class of models of the axioms, instead of the semantics being fixed to just the standard model as in the standard semantics.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] A model in Henkin semantics will provide a set of sets or set of functions as the interpretation of higher-order domains, which may be a proper subset of all sets or functions of that sort.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] For his axiomatisation, Henkin proved that Gödel's completeness theorem and compactness theorem, which hold for first-order logic, carry over to second-order logic with Henkin semantics.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Since also the Löwenheim–Skolem theorems hold for Henkin semantics, Lindström's theorem imports that Henkin models are just *disguised first-order models*.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Henkin semantics are commonly used in the study of second-order arithmetic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] For example, "we cannot meaningfully ask whether the V as defined in $\mathrm {ZFC}$ is the real V .
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Second-order logic is more expressive than first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] The rest of the first line represents the assumption that A is bounded from above (there exists a number z that is greater than or equal to all elements u of A ).
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] The second line expresses the existence of a least upper bound x .
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] It asserts that x is an upper bound (it is greater than or equal to any element u in A ) and that, if any number y is also an upper bound, then $x\leq y$ .
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Any ordered field that satisfies this property is isomorphic to the real number field.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] On the other hand, the set of first-order sentences valid in the reals has arbitrarily large models due to the compactness theorem.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Thus the least-upper-bound property cannot be expressed by any set of sentences in first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] In second-order logic, it is possible to write formal sentences that say “the domain is finite” or “the domain is of countable cardinality.” To say that the domain is finite, use the sentence that says that every surjective function from the domain to itself is injective.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] To say that the domain has countable cardinality, use the sentence that says that there is a bijection between every two infinite subsets of the domain.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] It follows from the compactness theorem and the upward Löwenheim–Skolem theorem that it is not possible to characterize finiteness or countability, respectively, in first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Certain fragments of second-order logic like ESO are also more expressive than first-order logic even though they are strictly less expressive than the full second-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] ESO also enjoys translation equivalence with some extensions of first-order logic that allow non-linear ordering of quantifier dependencies, like first-order logic extended with Henkin quantifiers, Hintikka and Sandu's independence-friendly logic, and Väänänen's dependence logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] A deductive system for a logic is a set of inference rules and logical axioms that determine which sequences of formulas constitute valid proofs.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Several deductive systems can be used for second-order logic, although none can be complete for the standard semantics (see below).
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Each of these systems is sound, which means any sentence they can be used to prove is logically valid in the appropriate semantics.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] The weakest deductive system that can be used consists of a standard deductive system for first-order logic (such as natural deduction) augmented with substitution rules for second-order terms.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] This deductive system is commonly used in the study of second-order arithmetic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] The deductive systems considered by Shapiro (2000) and Henkin (1950) add to the augmented first-order deductive scheme both comprehension axioms and choice axioms.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] These axioms are sound for standard second-order semantics.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] They are sound for Henkin semantics restricted to Henkin models satisfying the comprehension and choice axioms.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] One might attempt to reduce the second-order theory of the real numbers, with full second-order semantics, to the first-order theory in the following way.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] First expand the domain from the set of all real numbers to a two-sorted domain, with the second sort containing all *sets of* real numbers.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Add a new binary predicate to the language: the membership relation.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Then sentences that were second-order become first-order, with the formerly second-order quantifiers ranging over the second sort instead.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] This reduction can be attempted in a one-sorted theory by adding unary predicates that tell one whether an element is a number or a set, and taking the domain to be the union of the set of real numbers and the power set of the real numbers.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] But notice that the domain was asserted to include *all* sets of real numbers.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] That requirement cannot be reduced to a first-order sentence, or even a first-order theory, as the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem shows.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Countability of the set of all internal numbers (in conjunction with the fact that those form a densely ordered set) implies that that set does not satisfy the full least-upper-bound axiom.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Countability of the set of all *internal* sets implies that it is not the set of *all* subsets of the set of all *internal* numbers (since Cantor's theorem implies that the set of all subsets of a countably infinite set is an uncountably infinite set).
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] This construction is closely related to Skolem's paradox.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Thus the first-order theory of real numbers and sets of real numbers has many models, some of which are countable.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] The second-order theory of the real numbers has only one model, however.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] This follows from the classical theorem that there is only one Archimedean complete ordered field, along with the fact that all the axioms of an Archimedean complete ordered field are expressible in second-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] This shows that the second-order theory of the real numbers cannot be reduced to a first-order theory, in the sense that the second-order theory of the real numbers has only one model but the corresponding first-order theory has many models.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] There are more extreme examples showing that second-order logic with standard semantics is more expressive than first-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] There is a finite second-order theory whose only model is the real numbers if the continuum hypothesis holds and that has no model if the continuum hypothesis does not hold.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] This theory consists of a finite theory characterizing the real numbers as a complete Archimedean ordered field plus an axiom saying that the domain is of the first uncountable cardinality.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] This example illustrates that the question of whether a sentence in second-order logic is consistent is extremely subtle.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Additional limitations of second-order logic are described in the next section.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] This corollary is sometimes expressed by saying that second-order logic does not admit a complete proof theory.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] In this respect second-order logic with standard semantics differs from first-order logic; Quine pointed to the lack of a complete proof system as a reason for thinking of second-order logic as not *logic*, properly speaking.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] The compactness theorem and the Löwenheim–Skolem theorem do not hold for full models of second-order logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Predicate logic was introduced to the mathematical community by C.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Peirce, who coined the term *second-order logic* and whose notation is most similar to the modern form (Putnam 1982).
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] However, today most students of logic are more familiar with the works of Frege, who published his work several years prior to Peirce but whose works remained less known until Bertrand Russell and Alfred North Whitehead made them famous.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Frege used different variables to distinguish quantification over objects from quantification over properties and sets; but he did not see himself as doing two different kinds of logic.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] After the discovery of Russell's paradox it was realized that something was wrong with his system.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Eventually logicians found that restricting Frege's logic in various ways—to what is now called first-order logic—eliminated this problem: sets and properties cannot be quantified over in first-order logic alone.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] The now-standard hierarchy of orders of logics dates from this time.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] It was found that set theory could be formulated as an axiomatized system within the apparatus of first-order logic (at the cost of several kinds of completeness, but nothing so bad as Russell's paradox), and this was done (see Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory), as sets are vital for mathematics.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] This rejection was actively advanced by some logicians, most notably W.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] For example, it might mean “… is a dog.” But it makes no sense to think we can quantify over something like this.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] (Such a position is quite consistent with Frege's own arguments on the concept-object distinction.) So to use a predicate as a variable is to have it occupy the place of a name, which only individual variables should occupy.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] This reasoning has been rejected by George Boolos.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] In recent years second-order logic has made something of a recovery, buoyed by Boolos’ interpretation of second-order quantification as plural quantification over the same domain of objects as first-order quantification (Boolos 1984).
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Boolos furthermore points to the claimed nonfirstorderizability of sentences such as “Some critics admire only each other” and “Some of Fianchetto’s men went into the warehouse unaccompanied by anyone else”, which he argues can only be expressed by the full force of second-order quantification.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] However, generalized quantification and partially ordered (or branching) quantification may suffice to express a certain class of purportedly nonfirstorderizable sentences as well and these do not appeal to second-order quantification.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] The expressive power of various forms of second-order logic on finite structures is intimately tied to computational complexity theory.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] The field of descriptive complexity studies which computational complexity classes can be characterized by the power of the logic needed to express languages (sets of finite strings) in them.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Conversely, the Cayley tables of any finite structure (over a finite signature) can be encoded by a finite string.
[src:descriptive-complexity/second-order-logic] Relationships among these classes directly impact the relative expressiveness of the logics over finite structures; for example, if **PH** = **PSPACE**, then adding a transitive closure operator to second-order logic would not make it any more expressive over finite structures.
